<TEXT>
after 30 years of handling people in crisis 
the suicide prevention center has a crisis of its own half the 
telephone hotline workers have walked out in a dispute over layoffs 
and control of the center 
the workers went out on jan 1 and it has been a sometimes noisy 
dispute with striking counselors picketing the centers offices 
and chanting down with the board during a recent closeddoor 
meeting of directors 
despite the walkout the crisis line handled more calls in 
january than it did the same month a year earlier executive 
director sheila halfon said 
in fact the strike has prompted people to come forward to ask 
if the center needed their help 
we were deluged with calls from people who read about it and 
asked how could they volunteer halfon said 
in addition to the crisis line the center operates a substance 
abuse clinic a halfway house an aids research project an art 
therapy program and an annual curriculum for schools on substance 
abuse and suicide 
before the layoffs the center excluding crisis line workers 
had about 90 full and parttime employees the crisis line was 
staffed by about 80 volunteers and consultants the latter are 
workers who started out as volunteers but have begun to receive 
parttime 6anhour shifts 
the crisis line workers walked out when 27 of the noncrisis 
line staffers were laid off and the hours of 15 others were cut 
back late last year 
the layoff was strictly a budgetary concern halfon 
asserted though she admitted the timing was terrible you know 
december 
the centers budget in 198586 was about 3 million including 
revenue from contracts grants clinic fees and donations she said 
but in the last year some grants have ended and contracts that 
provided government funding have not been renewed she said 
estimating the current budget at about 15 million 
we are concerned with fulfilling that she said the 
cutbacks in just the layoffs will result in a savings of half a 
million dollars 
the strikers however are particularly upset that among those 
laid off was the centers first employee social worker sam heilig 
who served as a clinical consultant 
