a baby born with nearly no brain was 
on lifesupport equipment today as a potential organ donor after a 
similar infant was taken off life support machinery officials said 
both newborns born with the birth defect known as anencephaly 
or severely underdeveloped brains were part of a controversial 
program at loma linda university medical center preserving 
braindead anencephalic infants for use as organ donors 
the practice has drawn fire from righttolife groups charging 
cruelty and from medical ethicists who say it is questionable to 
keep the babies on life support when they have no chance at 
longterm survival 
evelyn keys born saturday in san antonio texas was flown to 
loma linda that night to be used in the donor program 
she arrived just hours after a child identified only as baby 
john was taken off life support when a worldwide search failed to 
turn up any needy organ recipients matching his tissue type said 
hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell 
but one of the infants heart valves was removed and stored for 
later use ms rockwell said 
anencephalic babies usually die shortly after birth and loma 
linda where infant heart transplants have become routine wants to 
establish a practice of sustaining such babies so their organs can 
be transplanted after brain death is certified by two independent 
physicians 
hospital officials said removal of baby johns heart valve was 
the first use of body parts from a us anencephalic infant loma 
linda previously transplanted the heart from an anencephalic baby 
declared braindead in canada 
baby evelyn was born to judy keys 22 and airman todd keys 21 
of the 6993rd electronic security squad at lackland air force base 
doctors report baby evelyn is resting comfortably and 
although there are some signs of brain stem deterioration she has 
not yet met all the criteria of brain death ms rockwell said 
today 
loma linda is the first hospital in the united states to develop 
a medical program allowing the practice of sustaining anencephalic 
infants for transplants 
if brain death does not occur within a week of birth an 
anencephalic baby will be removed from its respirator and allowed 
to die naturally 
several thousand anencephalic babies are born in the united 
states each year their brain stems can sustain basic functions 
such as breathing for a short time but death usually occurs within 
hours or days of birth 
loma linda has specialized in infant heart transplants with 13 
babies under the age of four months given new hearts at the 
hospital nine have survived 
