<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide when 
police need court warrants before searching from helicopters for 
marijuana growing in fencedin yards 
the justices said they will study a florida supreme court ruling 
that a helicopter search by sheriffs deputies in pasco county four 
years ago violated the right of privacy 
the nations highest court in 1986 ruled that a warrantless 
search by santa clara calif police in an airplane had not 
violated privacy rights 
in that case police spotted marijana plants growing in a 
fencedin yard while flying at a lawful altitude of 1000 feet 
voting 54 then the justices said the constitutions fourth 
amendment which bans unreasonable government searches simply 
does not require the police traveling in public airways at this 
altitude 1000 feet to obtain a warrant in order to observe what 
is visible to the naked eye 
in the florida case pasco county deputies received an anonymous 
tip that michael a riley was growing marijuana in his yard 
unable to tell what plants were growing in a greenhouse in the 
yard the deputies flew over the yard in a helicopter at an 
altitude of about 400 feet from there they could look into 
missing panels in the greenhouse roof 
based on what they saw the deputies obtained a search warrant 
and entered rileys yard seizing 44 marijuana plants 
riley challenged the helicopter search seeking to block 
prosecutors from using the marijuana plants as evidence against him 
the florida supreme court last july 9 ruled for riley stating 
that the helicopter search violated rileys reasonable expectation 
of privacy under the fourth amendment 
the state court said the 1986 decision did not authorize an 
unlimited right to any type of examination of residential property 
from the air 
the state court added surveillance by helicopter is 
particularly likely to unreasonably intrude upon private activities 
because of a helicopters virtually unlimited maneuverability 
and observational capabilities 
it noted that fixedwing airplanes are not authorized to fly 
lower than 500 feet in the area where the search occurred 
florida prosecutors filed the appeal acted on today 
the case is florida vs riley 87764 
</TEXT>
