<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear appeals 
by the reagan administration and coal mining companies seeking to 
block the possible award of billions of dollars in black lung 
disease benefits to thousands of miners 
the court said it will review a ruling that the government must 
reopen some previously rejected claims for benefits 
the administration said the ruling by a federal appeals court 
if extended nationwide could force officials to reexamine 94000 
claims at potentially tremendous cost to the overburdened fund that 
pays benefits to miners afflicted with the disease 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals last march ruled that 
thousands of miners seeking the benefits had been unfairly denied a 
hearing 
the ruling applied to miners with less than 10 years of work in 
the mines whose claims were denied in the late 1970s and early 
1980s 
the appeals court said the us department of labor must take a 
fresh look at the claims under liberalized standards adopted by 
congress in 1977 the appeals court applied the ruling to miners 
who failed to exhaust their administrative remedies or who missed 
deadlines for filing court appeals 
the appeals court said miners seeking benefits have 
encountered enormous frustration in the processing of their claims 
due to administrative delays and determinations under improper 
standards congress has repeatedly attempted to ease the burden of 
proof of disability and to expedite black lung claims 
the justice department said the ruling would force the labor 
department to embark on a potentially enormous reopening of 
closed cases that will impose a massive administrative burden the 
records for approximately 94000 claims would have to be retrieved 
and analyzed if the appeals court ruling were to apply nationwide 
the 8th circuit court has jurisdiction in north and south 
dakota minnesota nebraska iowa arkansas and missouri 
congress has created a special fund to pay off claims for miners 
with black lung disease also known as pneumonconiosis 
coal mine operators owe the government some 3 billion that has 
been loaned to the fund from the federal treasury 
the operators said the 8th circuit court ruling if applied 
nationwide could burden the industry with 136 billion in 
additional payments 
the us treasury will be required to borrow the money to pay 
these claims until the coal industry is able to do so if that day 
ever comes 
in another dispute over black lung benefits the supreme court 
in december made it easier for mining companies to block the award 
of some disability benefits that decision upheld a labor 
department rule that miners are not entitled to an interim 
presumption they were disabled by the disease based on a single 
piece of medical evidence 
the cases acted on today are pittston coal group vs sebben 
87821 and whitfield vs sebben 87827 
</TEXT>
