a forest fire sparked by a hikers campfire and fanned by 90 mph 
gusts slowed today after threatening up to 100 houses near boulder 
colo and a windwhipped 2400acre blaze in montana destroyed at 
least four houses 
no injuries were reported 
roads in colorados sunshine canyon area were closed late sunday 
and occupants of one apartment building near the blaze voluntarily 
left the building as did residents of five homes but no 
evacuations were ordered and the roads were reopened today 
the fire grew to more than 200 acres of grass and light timber 
by early today the boulder county sheriffs department said 
the area was under a high wind warning with 90 mph gusts 
reported wind had been expected to reach 100 mph today but at 3 
am it subsided to gusts of no more than 30 mph and there was an 
early morning calm of 6 mph the national weather service said 
the fire has laid down considerably since last night said 
firefighter john gregg its not contained in the sense that 
there is no fire line around the fire completely but its not 
spreading out of control as it was last night when the winds were 
high 
