<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that drastically limits the power of communities to regulate cable 
television and raises doubts about the constitutionality of a key 
federal law governing cable operations 
the court citing a lack of jurisdiction turned away an appeal 
by two california cities barred from enforcing public access and 
other rules challenged by a cable operator 
the courts action which appears to have been based on narrow 
procedural grounds leaves open the possibility of a subsequent 
appeal 
the dispute was between officials of palo alto and atherton 
calif and century federal inc the cable operator 
us district judge eugene f lynch ruled last september that 
cable regulations adopted by the cities unconstitutionally violated 
century federals freespeech rights 
he threw out regulations that required century federal 
to provide public access channels for those not connected with 
the cable company 
to wire the entire community to make service available to all 
residents 
to use a stateoftheart system to keep pace with the 
latest technological advances 
the judge who previously had ordered city officials to award an 
operating license to century federal called for further hearings 
to study franchise fee requirements adopted by the cities 
palo alto and atherton officials said the ruling appears to 
declare unconstitutional a 1984 federal law regulating cable tv 
even though the judge did not say in so many words he was 
invalidating the law 
although lynch purported not to decide the constitutionality 
of any provision of the act his decision in fact holds that 
numerous sections of that statute are unconstitutional lawyers 
for the cities said 
the reagan administration in a friendofthecourt legal 
brief filed by justice department lawyers urged the court to deny 
the cities appeal 
the supreme court in a 1986 ruling that has some bearing on the 
case acted on today raised the possibility that communities may be 
barred from granting exclusive cable tv franchises 
the court said cable franchise activities plainly implicate 
first amendment interests but the justices stopped short of a 
definitive ruling on the constitutional rights of cable operators 
the ruling was in contrast to earlier decisions denying a 
constitutional right to operate overtheair television or radio 
stations 
many cities award exclusive cable franchises citywide or for 
various regions within the city they also impose rules similar to 
those adopted by palo alto and atherton 
the case is palo alto vs century federal 87946 
</TEXT>
