<TEXT>
navy secretary james h webb resigned today 
saying he is unable to support defense secretary frank 
carluccis decision to abandon the goal of a 600ship fleet and 
criticizing carluccis leadership in the pentagon 
this building needs to be led webb told reporters it 
needs leadership it needs some vision im saying that if i had a 
piece of advice to give to secretary carlucci it would be to spend 
a lot more time with the top leaders in this building 
hes been spending a lot of time with the state department and 
a lot of time on the hill i think they pentagon leaders need to 
feel his vision and to understand what he believes in 
webb 42 has held the job less than a year a highlydecorated 
marine veteran of vietnam combat he was the author of fields of 
fire a bestselling novel about the war in vietnam 
in his letter of resignation to president reagan webb said he 
decided to leave because he could not support the fiscal 1989 
pentagon budget proposal crafted by carlucci 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said secretary 
carlucci is having to make some very difficult adjustments in the 
pentagon to accommodate budgetary reductions secretary webb 
indicates he is unable to operate under these constraints but i 
know the president feels he has given very valuable service to the 
country and will work with secretary carlucci to find a 
replacement as soon as possible 
referring to the internal budget debate that led to last weeks 
submission of the fiscal 1989 budget webb wrote to reagan 
on three separate occasions the uniformed and civilian 
leadership of the navy department provided the secretary of defense 
with proposed cuts totaling the amount required to meet the budget 
reduction but which also would preserve the cherished goal of your 
administration to rebuild our navy to a minimum of 600 ships 
because those recommendations were rejected by your secretary 
of defense i am unable to support him personally or to defend this 
amended budget during budget deliberations on capitol hill 
webb concluded 
consequently i find it necessary to resign from my position 
as secretary of the navy 
this budget cutting is not being done according to a 
strategy webb told reporters in his pentagon office 
webb who assumed the post as the navys top civilian leader 
just april 10 said his concerns focused on a decision by carlucci 
to propose the early retirement and mothballing of 16 navy frigates 
the navy had to cut 12 billion from its original fiscal 1989 
budget plan but still could have kept those ships by assigning 
them to the naval reserve instead of consigning them to mothballs 
webb continued 
without those frigates webb said there was no way the navy 
could build to 600 warships in fiscal 1989 as originally planned 
indeed despite the optimistic predictions of other pentagon 
officials the decision means the navy will never reach the 
600ship mark he added 
and one of the sad things about this this was one of the few 
goals of the reagan administration that was really obtainable at 
pretty low cost webb added 
webb one of the youngest men to ever become navy secretary is 
a naval academy graduate 
he came to the pentagon in 1984 when caspar w weinberger was 
the defense secretary assuming the post of assistant defense 
secretary for reserve affairs webb had resigned that position and 
was preparing to leave government service in early 1987 when the 
president asked him to replace john f lehman the first navy 
secretary of the reagan administration 
in his meeting with reporters webb declined to speculate on why 
carlucci had insisted that ships be retired when that step in 
webbs view wasnt required 
pentagon leaders should always be concerned about hollow 
forces that arent properly manned but the navy could have 
reached the 600ship mark without giving up readiness webb 
insisted 
the navy secretary said he had wrestled with his concerns for 
some time but didnt make a final decision to resign until sunday 
webb said he had not spoken to carlucci today but had sent him 
a copy of his letter to reagan 
carlucci in a written personal statement said today he had 
learned of webbs decision with regret 
i wish him well in his future endeavors carlucci said he 
has earned our respect and gratitude for his service to our nation 
both in uniform and as a civilian leader within the defense 
department 
the pentagon in a companion statement said the recent budget 
debate has been one of the most painful in history 
the compromises have not been easy for anyone and we regret 
the fact that the secretary of the navy appears to have found 
himself unable to defend the departments decisions under the 
circumstances he has done the honorable thing 
</TEXT>
