<TEXT>
president reagan asked the senate on monday to 
ratify a treaty with canada that he said should help the two 
countries prosecute terrorists drug traffickers and other 
criminals 
the treaty on mutual legal assistance in criminal matters was 
signed by reagan and canadian prime minister brian mulroney at 
their meeting in quebec city canada on march 18 1985 the white 
house said submission was delayed while annexes to the pact were 
worked out by the two nations 
it is one of a series of such legal assistance treaties being 
negotiated by the united states 
similar pacts have gone into force with italy the netherlands 
switzerland and turkey 
others have been signed but not yet gone into force with 
colombia morocco mexico thailand belgium the bahamas and the 
united kingdom on behalf of the cayman islands 
reagan sent the treaty with mexico to the senate for 
consideration just before his meeting with mexican president miguel 
de la madrid in mazatlan mexico on feb 13 
in his message to the senate he said the treaty with canada 
should be an effective tool to prosecute a wide variety of modern 
criminals including members of drug cartels whitecollar 
criminals and terrorists 
the treaty provides for the two countries to assist each other 
in taking testimony or statements of witnesses providing 
documents records and evidence executing requests for searches 
and seizures and serving documents 
it also provides for assistance in proceedings relating to 
forfeiture of the proceeds of crime restitution for victims and 
collection of fines 
</TEXT>
