governors push for welfare reform emerged from the meeting and 
said he felt reagan was open to compromise 
i am encouraged because basically their negotiating strategy 
with everybody always is to take the hardest possible line and then 
come off of it at the end clinton said 
in the private meeting that followed reagans speech clinton 
said i told him we thought his bill was not a good bill and that 
we were willing to make some changes in what came out of the house 
but we werent going to get anywhere if his emissary kept saying 
well were going to veto whatever passes that we dont like 
clinton said reagan replied that he heard us and was 
willing to work with us so i think thats good 
alabama gov guy hunt a republican said he shared reagans 
misgivings about the housepassed welfare bill he said it might 
really compound the problem by increasing federal funding without 
giving states more control over welfare rules 
what the states need is flexibility to allow them to gradually 
remove people from welfare instead of terminating their 
benefits as soon as they get a job hunt said 
later the governors committee on human resources heard 
televisions captain kangaroo bob keeshan plead for corporations 
to start providing quality day care im almost ashamed at times 
to be an american the childrens performer and advocate said 
we are half a century behind in addressing day care we are going 
to pay an enormous price a quartercentury down the line 
