<TEXT>
a federal judge on monday dismissed a lawsuit 
challenging the constitutionality of new sentencing guidelines 
ruling that two public defender offices lacked legal standing to 
bring the case 
the decision by us district judge stanley sporkin dismissed 
the case on technical grounds it came four days after two federal 
judges in california had held the new sentencing guidelines were 
unconstitutional 
the two judges in san diego ruled that the 1984 law establishing 
the us sentencing commission was unconstitutional because it 
improperly placed the panel in the judicial instead of the 
executive branch in violation of the constitutions 
separationofpowers doctrine 
unlike the california cases the suit before sporkin did not 
involve defendants who faced sentencing under the new guidelines 
which provide a complicated set of factors for determining the 
length of a defendants incarceration 
sporkin found that federal public defenders offices in san 
diego and nashville lacked legal standing to sue because they 
couldnt show they were harmed by the new sentencing guidelines 
permitting lawyers to sue without clients or at best with 
only potential clients merely because their putatative clients 
allegedly will be harmed would open the same door for specialist 
lawyers to sue whenever congress enacts a statute which impacts on 
their clientele sporkin said 
the harm alleged by plaintiffs essentially boils down to 
their perception that their workload will be more complex and will 
markedly increase sporkin said 
that sort of harm or injury is no different from the 
harm that the passage of the tax reform act of 1986 caused for 
tax laywers or for that matter than the harm caused for criminal 
lawyers by the passage of the bail reform and speedy trial acts 
the judge said 
</TEXT>
