<TEXT>
japan is asking the united states to 
reconsider its charges that a japanese scientific research 
whaling expedition in the antarctic is undermining international 
agreements the japanese embassy said monday 
ambassador nobuo matsunaga sent secretary of state george shultz 
a letter accusing the united states of taking unilateral action 
and unjustifiable measures in the whaling dispute an embassy 
statement said 
it referred to a feb 10 commerce department declaration that 
japans killing of minke whales in the antarctic violated 
international whaling agreements the declaration means that 
president reagan by april can order a 50 percent cut in the 
japanese fishing quota in us economic territorial waters and 
exclude japanese fish and fish products from us markets 
the current japanese fishing quota in the 200mile offshore us 
economic zone is zero but the declaration could be applied to 
future years as well as apply to sales of processed fish 
matsunagas letter restated the japanese government position 
that the current antarctic expedition is for noncommercial 
research provided for in the international whaling commission 
convention the united states and japan agreed in 1984 that japan 
would cease commercial whaling in 1987 
critics say that proposed harvest of hundreds of minke whales is 
excessive for research that the commission has not specifically 
authorized the current expedition and that the stated research into 
whale population diet and nutrition could be carried out without 
killing the whales 
the embassy said matsunaga in his letter dated friday 
strongly urged the us to reconsider its position in light of 
the damage these moves would cause to mutually beneficial 
usjapan fishery relations 
