<TEXT>
they worshipped in village homes at night 
they hid the symbols of their foreign faith inside buddhist altars 
and images these were times when their discovery could mean 
torture or death 
they were japanese who became christians after st francis 
xavier visited japan in 15491551 
today japans christians worship freely but they cherish their 
secret past 
some 13000 of the nations 1 million or so christians continue 
the tradition of secret worship mostly on remote islands in 
southern japan most are the elderly who do so out of habit rather 
than out of fear 
and now artifacts of the secretchristian era many collected by 
a woman who once worshipped secretly herself soon will be 
displayed in a museum here in oiso 
hundreds of thousands of japanese embraced christianity under 
jesuit and roman catholic leadership in the 16th century when 
western influence was first felt in their isolated archipelago 
the government banned what it regarded as a disruptive foreign 
religion after europeans were expelled from japan in 1639 in 
periodic persecutions suspected christians were forced to recant 
or be tortured crucified or burned at the stake 
but christians continued to worship privately for more than 200 
years and during that time japanese christianity acquired a 
unique flavor 
the hundreds of statues and scrolls already collected by the 
museum at oiso attest to the ambiguity of religion in japan where 
adherents to various faiths have customarily mixed christian 
buddhist and shinto rituals to mark the major turning points in 
their lives 
as the christians originally concentrated in kyushu gradually 
spread throughout japan they preserved symbols of their faith in 
hidden ways said shigeru tai the curator of the museums 
collection 
carpenters built crosses into buddhist temples he said 
they worshipped symbols of fish and family crests that were 
shaped like crosses and other japanese didnt guess those were 
also christian symbols 
in one temple the walls were studded with crossshaped 
windows but the buddhist priests had no idea they were made by 
christians 
the secret christians took advantage of this lack of awareness 
and of the close similarity of the christian madonna and the 
buddhist god of mercy they painted on their breasts tiny gold 
crucifixes that apparently passed unnoticed 
the back of one artifact a statue of a japanese warriorgod 
brandishing a spear opens to reveal an ivory and gold crucifix 
other statues have false bottoms with crosses and icons inside 
tai 71 was a close friend of miki sawada the woman who 
collected the treasures and the granddaughter of the founder of the 
mitsubishi industrial empire 
after her death in 1980 tai and others raised the funds for the 
museum on the peaceful forested grounds of the orphanage mrs 
sawada founded in oiso 35 miles southwest of tokyo 
born into a strict buddhist family she learned of christianity 
from a nurse when she was 8 years old and worshipped secretly until 
her 18th birthday when she was allowed to attend a church service 
for the first time 
she eventually married a christian and devoted her life and 
wealth to helping others establishing the elizabeth saunders home 
for orphans the orphanage was named after an impoverished british 
woman living in japan who contributed her life savings 170 to 
help establish it 
for 40 years mrs sawada visited communities where secret 
christians once lived collecting their treasures which are being 
housed in a tiny chapel before the museums opening in april 
these items are priceless said tai gingerly uncovering 
what looks like a metal plate but turns out to be a magic mirror 
there is only one man in japan who can still make these mirrors 
bright light reflected in the rather dull surface of the 16th 
century mirror casts the shadow of christ on the cross to police 
seeking out christians at the time the mirror was just a mirror 
but for the secret worshipers it was a precious symbol of their 
faith 
the prohibition on christianity enforced sporadically was 
lifted when japan reopened its door to the west in 1854 under the 
militaristic governments during world war ii however christianity 
again became suspect 
some secret christians willingly worshipped both buddhist and 
christian deity others forced to demonstrate their piety at 
temples and shrines directed their prayers toward crosses etched 
secretly by other christians into woodwork or hidden behind 
buddhist altars 
when japanese pray at shrines and temples they usually clap 
twice the christians would clap once again the third clap a 
reminder of the holy trinity tai said 
during the war when christianity was considered subversive 
we used to clap the third clap very quietly he said 
christianity however has set down few roots in this syncretic 
nation and today attracts less than 1 percent of japans 121 
million people 
less than half the japanese people profess devotion to any 
faith but japanese life is still dominated by buddhist and shinto 
rites and most homes have buddhist altars for prayers to dead 
family members 
the christians still living in remote villages in southern 
japan who say prayers in an incomprehensible form of pidgin 
japanese are continuing a tradition that is dying elsewhere tai 
said 
</TEXT>
