<TEXT>
allan hendrickse a mixedrace 
politician and member of president p w bothas cabinet defied 
apartheid laws more than a year ago and went swimming at a 
whitesonly beach then at bothas demand he apologized 
doubts immediately arose that the highly regarded hendrickse 
would ever regain credibility among his nonwhite constituents 
but he has made a remarkable comeback 
hendrickse now is recognized as perhaps the only elected 
official in south africa with both the will and the power to defy 
the president 
as leader of parliaments mixedrace chamber he is in a 
position to force bothas national party to the polls next year 
three years earlier than it would like 
botha he needs consent from all three chambers of parliament to 
delay the election from 1989 to 1992 hendrickse whose labor party 
holds 76 of 85 seats in the house of representatives says he wont 
acquiesce unless botha abandons the governments policy of 
segregated neighborhoods 
this demand is unlikely to be met and has resulted in 
hendrickses forced resignation from the cabinet but the 
confrontation appears to have boosted his popularity among the 
countrys 3 million coloreds as mixedrace south africans are 
called 
suddenly a lot of people who were disinterested or 
antagonistic are now realizing that you can find yourself in a 
position of altering the course of history in this country 
hendrickse 60 said at a recent news briefing it does give you 
and the people you represent a feeling of importance 
hendrickses political fortunes have seesawed since he helped 
found the labor party in 1969 
he was detained for two months in 1976 for his antiapartheid 
stance but came under fire from activists in 1984 when the labor 
party agreed to participate in a new tricameral parliament setup 
chambers for asians and coloreds were created to join the dominant 
white chamber although the nations black majority remained 
excluded 
the asian and mixedrace chambers are allowed to handle their 
own affairs deciding to how to allocate public funding for 
their own communities for example but the 1984 constitution gives 
the majority party in the white chamber almost total power to set 
national policy and to override even combined opposition from the 
other chambers 
hendrickse said he would cooperate with the new system for five 
years in an effort to dismantle apartheid from within activists 
nonetheless denounced him as a sellout for joining bothas cabinet 
as minister without portfolio 
our participation within the system must not be construed as 
an acceptance of the system said hendrickse we walk the 
difficult road of being in and yet being out 
in january 1987 the portly politician made a seemingly bold 
challenge of the government by wading into the surf at a 
whitesonly beach in port elizabeth 
botha in a televised speech furiously ordered hendrickse to 
apologize or quit the cabinet hendrickse apologized 
it was a demolition job with such humiliation for rev 
hendrickse that he is unlikely to recover from it peter gastrow 
chairman of the white opposition progressive federal party said at 
the time 
now white liberals applaud hendrickses tougher tactics and are 
considering possible alliances with his labor party 
hendrickse still has many detractors including activists who 
totally reject the tricameral parliament at the university of the 
western cape a leftist predominantly mixedrace school rector 
jakes gerwel said hendrickses resurgence had been a nonevent 
the progovernment media also has been critical for different 
reasons the citizen a johannesburg newspaper maintained that the 
labor party had become fractious and militant after being set 
on a dangerous collision course by hendricske 
hendrickse says he holds no personal animosity toward botha but 
is clearly pleased at having found an effective means of 
challenging him 
its not a question of personal power or strength but rather 
a recognition of the correctness of the decision to participate in 
parliament he said in spite of the constitutional 
inadequacies we were able to find a gap a weakness and thus find 
ourselves in a powerful position 
in addition to his leverage over the election schedule 
hendrickse has blocked a government proposal to begin joint debates 
among the three parliamentary chambers without joint voting and 
other reforms the change is meaningless hendrickse maintains 
regardless of whether the white election is delayed hendrickse 
wants mixedrace elections to proceed as scheduled next year only 
30 percent of colored voters went to the polls in 1984 when 
activists urged a boycott and hendrickse says the turnout next 
year could rise to 50 percent 
he said progovernment forces are seeking to weaken him by 
dividing his party allegations have surfaced that national party 
officials tried to bribe labor party members into deserting him 
there is speculation that botha may retire soon and hendrickse 
has raised an intriguing scenario regarding the choice of a 
successor by the electoral college 
the college consists of 50 national party members 25 labor 
party members and 13 members from the asian chambers majority 
party hendrickse says the asian and mixedrace electors could 
thwart the selection of a hardliner if they could persuade seven or 
more relatively liberal nationalists to join them in electing a 
moderate such as foreign minister roelof pik botha no 
relation to the president 
hendrickse was raised in uitenhage near port elizabeth the 
fifth child of a congregational minister he grew up in an 
integrated neighborhood and became a minister himself 
in 1971 the mixedrace community was forced to move to a 
colored township under terms of the group areas act which mandates 
segregated neighborhoods hendrickse has described his fathers 
anguish as he watched their home and church being destroyed 
now he wants the national party to abolish the group areas act 
and says he has done enough compromising 
</TEXT>
