<TEXT>
this is one of a series of periodic reports by 
associated press correspondents on the way of life in other 
countries 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
india is taking the bullockcart into 
the 21st century 
at least 500 researchers in about a dozen governmentaided 
institutes are at work modernizing the ancient creaking plodding 
carts and even the world bank has donated funds carts of various 
shapes and designs made of plastic and aluminum are being tested 
or have been developed 
there is nothing funny about our project said mittar pal 
dhir director of the road research institute in new delhi for 
us animaldrawn carts are of great importance 
india has an estimated 13 million bullock carts drawn by about 
26 million of the neutered bulls along with 2 million carts pulled 
by water buffaloes camels horses mules and donkeys 
the carts are seen most often in villages where about 640 
million of the indias 800 million people live 
but they also are seen on major highways and an estimated 3 
million plod along city streets often slowing enginepowered 
traffic and infuriating motorists 
bullock carts have even been used to pull mig fighter jets to 
parades and earth satellites to launching pads 
dhir said it would be 50 years before india could eliminate 
animaldrawn carts given their crucial role in indian life 
capital investment in animaldrawn carts is put at 76 billion 
more than 20 million indians earn their living by driving 
renting and repairing the carts 
the figure is striking given the fact that indian railways 
the fourth largest in the world employ only 163 million people 
said rupinder gupta a mechanical engineer for the road research 
institute gupta has designed six types of bullock cart for field 
trials 
each year animaldrawn carts move 144 million tonmiles of 
freight 
dhir estimates that indias animaldrawn carts provide about 40 
million horsepower equal to about 320000 mediumduty trucks used 
in the united states as city delivery vehicles 
without bullock carts india also would have had to import an 
additional 6 million tons of fuel each year it now imports 17 
million tons of crude oil annually 
one of the innovations is the replacement of the carts 
woodenspoke wheels with pneumatic tires 
engineer gupta said carts with pneumatic tires can pull 25 tons 
of weight against the maximum capacity of 15 tons for conventional 
carts 
researchers in the southern state of karnataka also have come up 
with plastic bullock carts and in neighboring andhra pradesh state 
a tire company has produced carts of lightweight aluminum 
another idea behind nonwooden carts is to reduce demand for 
lumber an estimated 165000 mediumsized trees are felled each 
year to make conventional carts 
so you see there is a solid logic behind metal carts said 
gupta 
he listed other reasons for updating the carts 
we want to increase tillage and output reduce damage to roads 
and injury to animals so that the poor animals can have a longer 
lifespan he said 
to protect the animals curved and padded yokes are being 
introduced studies have shown that some draft animals lives are 
cut short by cancerous infections on the neck from unpadded and 
uncurved yokes 
reflectors are being added as another safety feature 
other new fittings are bush bearings castiron springs shock 
absorbers draw bars that adjust for animals of different height 
and mud scrappers 
a fodder box can be put on carts that go long distances 
as for road damage director dhir said the biggest culprit is 
wooden wheels 
in monetary terms the annual damage is to the tune of 7000 
million rupees 538 million to the roads he said 
farmers seem to like the idea of improving bullock carts 
it is an excellent idea said jhandu singh 64 of jharsa a 
village 30 miles south of new delhi 
but this should have had been done 25 years ago we have 
suffered for long and so did the animals 
officials too say the new carts are catching on but this 
itself is creating problems 
we do not have enough new types of carts for all said kalle 
khan project economist of the district rural development agency in 
jharsa whose office received only 16 new carts 
there are more than 200 claimants even some gypsies saw the 
carts and were attracted they wanted at least one i told them no 
these are for farmers 
another reason for high demand is that the government is 
subsidizing the price by about 35 percent 
it is estimated that the largest of the old wooden carts costs 
the equivalent of about 300 newer wooden carts without the 
government subsidy cost 270 to 460 the plastic and aluminum 
carts are 25 percent more expensive 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0222 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
editors note the former mayor of syracuse ny will be 
sentenced this week on charges that he extorted hundreds of 
thousands of dollars from people wanting to do business with the 
city lee alexander a democrat pleaded guilty to the charges 
saying he accepted sole responsibility for what happened 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in his day lee alexander was one of the 
most visible mayors in america a politician who seemed destined 
for bigger things 
now he appears destined for prison 
as mayor of new yorks fifthlargest city alexander had a 
penchant for beautiful women chauffeurdriven limos and 
bodyguards he was a snappy dresser with a deep tan his hair 
always in place 
during his 16 years as mayor alexander a democrat was often 
the spokesman for the nations mayors he served as president of 
the us conference of mayors and six times was elected president 
of the national conference of democratic mayors 
there was talk of a big job in washington speculation that he 
might some day run for governor party leaders made him their 
candidate for the us senate in 1974 but he lost the primary to 
former us attorney general ramsey clark 
now it turns out the man who looked so urbane and polished was 
actually an extortionist using his power to coerce money from 
people wanting to do business with the city of syracuse 
alexanders scheme preyed on architects lawyers engineers and 
insurance agents they paid him up to 25 percent of the cost of the 
project and payments were made in bonds gold coins and cash 
for example an architect paid alexander 125000 for the 
opportunity to work on a project at the citys hancock 
international airport and another paid 25500 for a hospital 
parking garage expansion an insurance agent paid an alexander 
bagman 26200 for a fire policy and a lawyer paid a bagman 2878 
to handle the legal work on a downtown building project 
a lot of people turned down the deals and nothing happened 
said us attorney frederick j scullin alexander was astute 
enough to know where he could put the pressure if someone caved 
in well he kept the pressure on if someone rebuffed him right 
away hed back right up 
by the time alexander left city hall in 1986 he was a 
millionaire 
now he has to pay it all back 
alexander pleaded guilty to charges that he violated federal 
racketeering laws by using his power as mayor to extort money that 
he conspired to obstruct the investigation and that he evaded 
income taxes on his illegal profits 
sentencing is scheduled for march 10 
the federal prosecutor is recommending that alexander be 
sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined 100000 scullin said he 
believes that a 10year sentence would be longer than any handed to 
a public corruption figure in the nation 
alexander could have faced 690 years in prison if convicted on 
all 40 counts of the original indictment 
the former mayor has also agreed to return 12 million of his 
illegal profits alexander has said the settlement will leave him 
in worse financial shape than he was in 1970 when he began his 
mayoral career 
some of alexanders bounty was turned over to prosecutors by 
attorneys delivering shopping bags filled with valuable bonds and 
coupons some of the money was banked overseas in such places as 
the bahamas and panama according to scullin 
nine other people who have pleaded guilty to charges stemming 
from the investigation will be sentenced along with alexander 
alexanders undoing started with scullins appointment as us 
attorney for northern new york in 1982 scullin who grew up in 
syracuse and earned his law degree from syracuse university said 
he had heard talk that alexander was crooked 
this thing really began when i first became us attorney 
scullin says there were rumors on the street then about 
alexander being a wheeler and a dealer if not kickbacks then 
there was talk about a lot of conflicts the rumors were pretty 
rampant i decided we should look into it and put them to rest one 
way or another 
at first it was slow going but the investigation persisted 
you keep working and working nibbling away at it developing 
whatever information you can scullin says there was a pattern 
of nobid contracts and professional fees 
we got a couple of breaks we got lucky 
the internal revenue service and the fbi joined scullins 
attorneys in the investigation a witness came forward offering 
information in exchange for immunity that was the crack in the 
dam scullin says 
at its peak alexander was the focus of attention of a team of 
prosecutors 20 fbi agents and another 20 irs agents 
what they came up with was enough evidence to persuade a grand 
jury to indict the mayor 
alexander always seemed on the verge of becoming a political 
heavyweight 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in 1976 he passed up an opportunity to be an early supporter of 
jimmy carters presidential campaign to serve as upstate campaign 
coordinator for the illfated campaign of henry jackson 
his extortion scheme was designed to increase his influence with 
national politicians according to scullin 
he wanted to be considered a viable influence on the 
democratic party and make things happen scullin said he could 
get the money where other people could not 
many of the kickbacks alexander arranged were made in the form 
of political contributions to bigtime democrats scullin said new 
york city mayor ed koch gov mario cuomo and massachusetts gov 
michael dukakis were among the recipients 
toward the end he sort of lost track of the political 
contributions scullins said as he could see his star 
dwindling the last three or four years i think he was more 
concerned about lining his own pockets he got greedier and 
greedier as time went on 
opponents were critical of alexanders frequent trips away from 
syracuse saying he was more interested in traveling than tending 
to local problems alexander defended his travels saying he came 
back with federal money for his city 
alexander found an opportunity to get some publicity one day 
when a gunman killed a man then took a pregnant woman and her baby 
hostage in a predominantly black neighborhood holding police off 
for most of the day 
after being held back by police for many hours news 
photographers were suddenly allowed to approach the house the door 
opened and alexander ran out of the house clutching the baby to his 
chest photographs of the mayor carrying the baby to safety were 
displayed by newspapers across the country the next day black 
leaders complained that it was the only time alexander had ever 
visited the neighborhood 
on the local level alexander was a skillful and effective 
politician until alexander came along the republicans dominated 
syracuse and onondaga county politics alexanders campaign not 
only ended a 16year republican rule of the mayors office but led 
the democrats to control of the common council 
not everyone liked alexander when shots were fired at his 
house police were prompted to build a guardhouse outside the home 
city auditor roy bernardi was probably alexanders most vocal 
critic bernardis complaints were aimed mainly at the way the 
mayor did business 
the auditor said he knew then that the city was paying too much 
money for projects and was always doing business with the same 
people 
i noticed a pattern that if not illegal and i had no proof of 
that it was not in the best interest of the city said bernardi 
who is still the city auditor 
ironically while alexander was in power his republican 
opponents who controlled surrounding onondaga county were the 
target of a special prosecutor investigating political corruption 
despite the talk on the street the special prosecutor didnt pay 
much attention to the democrats 
the special prosecutor was appointed by thengov hugh carey a 
democrat to investigate allegations that republicans illegally 
coerced political contributions from public workers the 
investigation netted convictions against several key republicans 
who claimed they were unfairly singled out for activities common in 
politics and also practiced by city hall democrats 
but the crimes of the republicans pale when compared with what 
was going on in alexanders city hall office 
the republicans were convicted of violations of a state law 
prohibiting political fundraising in public buildings and 
misdemeanors juries returned acquittals on the more serious 
charges no republicans went to prison and no democrats were ever 
indicted in that special investigation 
alexander is not talking publicly about his troubles his lawyer 
said after making his guilty plea alexander issued a statement 
saying the city never paid for any services it did not receive 
i accept sole responsibility for what happened alexander 
said in his statement while pursuing the highest standards of 
integrity with respect to the conduct of members of my 
administration i did not apply those same standards to myself 
tom young a democrat is the mayor now and he runs things 
differently instead of personally selecting who does business with 
the city young has contractors submit competitive bids young has 
a panel study the proposals before a contract is awarded 
there are many who still believe alexander was good for syracuse 
i never saw any sign of any wrongdoing says robert visser 
the city clerk who has worked in city hall since 1974 
he did an awful lot of good for the city and eventually the 
good will outweigh the bad if it had not been for the former 
mayor the city of syracuse would not be in the great shape it is 
in today 
