editors note janwillem van de wetering wrote his first book 
at age 40 after years of hopping around the globe and pursuing an 
interest in zen buddhism the dutchborn author who now lives in 
maine was interviewed in new york where he was visiting his 
publisher 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fans of offbeat mysteries set in exotic locales 
dote on dutch author janwillem van de wetering a former amsterdam 
cop who spent two years in a zen buddhist monastery in japan 
but even though his novels often have a zen flavor van de 
wetering says the three heroes of what his publisher calls the 
amsterdam cop series are not followers of the oriental philosophy 
theyve never heard of buddhism or zen says van de 
wetering who now makes his home in maine drawn there first by a 
zen teacher i mention it sometimes in a joking manner because 
its popular with the dutch intelligentsia the police couldnt 
care less they think its all longhaired nonsense 
yet their supercool investigations read like theyre following 
the zen practice of attaining enlightenment by intuitive insight 
beyond intellectual reasoning 
a lot of people do that van de wetering says if you 
cant figure it out then dont try to figure it out but stay with 
it 
van de wetering now 56 wrote his first book when he was 40 it 
was the empty mirror about his experiences in the zen 
monastery 
he has written three childrens books two novels two books 
about zen a biography of dutch diplomatauthor robert van gulik 
and is best known for 12 mysteries most set in amsterdam 
the first mystery van de wetering wrote outsider in 
amsterdam introduced the wonderfully detached commissaris a 
dutch municipal police officer and his underlings in the murder 
brigade adjutant grijpstra and sgt de gier 
originally i wanted to write a realistic book about the 
police van de wetering said during a visit to new york to visit 
his publisher i had been a policeman myself and thought i could 
do it it never came off even at first none of the characters 
wanted to do that 
grijpstra was going to be the nasty guy he immediately became 
sympathetic he is my dutchman my everyman my superego he is not 
into fantasy i intended him to be pretty dumb but he isnt 
de gier turned out to have tremendous energy that everybody 
has as a child and then it gets repressed and organized by society 
with de gier it never got organized he is not in the police for 
any good purpose hes an adventurer hes tremendously curious he 
wants to see what goes on he doesnt necessarily sympathize with 
goodness and frown on evilness 
the only one whos got it all together is the commissaris he 
looks like a gray mouse with his limp but he really is a 
combination of them and goes beyond both of them he is what i 
think a zen master ought to be like the commissaris is convinced 
it doesnt matter what you do but he will always do the nice 
thing 
two of van de weterings mysteries have been made into movies in 
holland contracts for an american movie have been signed for 
hard rain published in 1986 by pantheon ballantine has 
published all the mysteries and the two books about zen in 
paperback 
the author whose name is pronounced yanvillum van de 
vettevin started visiting a zen teacher on the coast of maine in 
the 1960s in 1975 he and his colombian wife juanita settled 
nearby he became disillusioned with the zen teacher but stayed in 
maine because he likes the country his wife took up gardening 
their daughter is married 
we live on 60 acres which is quite normal there he says 
i see my neighbors when i go look for them but too many artists 
hang out in that part of the world we meet each other in endless 
encounters that consume too much time i really have to discipline 
myself when i go to the post office not to lose all day 
the weather is so interesting we all have boats theres a 
big colony of seals and we talk about what they do and what bird is 
coming for the summer or leaving for the winter 
i have very little discipline if i dont want to work i peer 
at the window and hope the dog will come in when i want to work 
ill work through the night and the next day wont go to the post 
office 
van de weterings hobby is making junk sculpture which he 
displays around his property 
i was always frantic about finding certain parts an old man 
said just let it come to you i do that all the time now when i 
turned 50 i was worried about dying i wanted a vehicle to guide 
me across a horse the afternoon i thought of it i went to the 
beach and found legs and ribs a sheet of plywood that was a 
wonderful fit and rope for the tail 
van de wetering learned about the amsterdam police work during 
seven years in the reserve police working mostly nights and 
weekends 
i had to do it because i got accused of dodging the draft i 
left holland when i was 19 and never remembered to come back it 
was kind of a punishment i liked it after four years i could have 
quit 
at 19 van de wetering went to south africa to work then to 
england to study philosophy for a year 
dissatisfied with western philosophy he spent two years in a 
zen monastery in kyoto japan after that he worked for a chemical 
company in colombia in real estate in australia returned to 
amsterdam to take over his uncles wholesale textile business he 
got bored with that sold it after seven years and moved to maine 
he started to write during the seven years in amsterdam 
i always wanted to write he says i couldnt i did bits 
and pieces and articles i read that henry miller started when he 
was 40 i kept the desire alive i started writing when i was 40 
</TEXT>
